.Dd April 15, 2026
.Dt B76PIPE 3
.Os
.Sh NAME
.Nm b76pipe
.Nd Base76 streaming pipeline encoder/decoder with optional custom alphabet
.Sh SYNOPSIS
.Nm b76pipe
.Op Fl r
.Op Fl i Ar infile
.Op Fl o Ar outfile
.Op Fl -alpha Ar alphabet_file
.Op Ar message
.Pp
.Nm b76pipe
.Fl h
.Pp
.Nm b76pipe
.Fl -help
.Pp
.Nm b76pipe
.Fl -version
.Sh DESCRIPTION
The
.Nm
utility implements a reversible Base76 pipeline using a 7-bit safe alphabet.
It can operate in forward mode (bytes to Base76 tokens) or reverse mode
(Base76 tokens to bytes).
Input may be provided as a message argument or read from a file.
Output may be written to a file or to standard output.
.Pp
By default, the Base76 alphabet is taken from
.Pa base76_alphabet.h .
The
.Fl -alpha
option allows overriding the alphabet at runtime using an external file.
.Pp
The pipeline operates in a streaming fashion and does not load the entire
input into memory.
Forward mode processes input byte-by-byte, and reverse mode processes Base76
tokens one at a time.
This allows processing of arbitrarily large inputs, limited only by I/O
capacity.
.Sh OPTIONS
.Bl -tag -width Ds
.It Fl r
Run the pipeline in reverse mode (Base76 tokens to bytes).
.It Fl i Ar infile
Read input from
.Ar infile .
When this option is used, any
.Ar message
argument is ignored.
.It Fl o Ar outfile
Write output to
.Ar outfile .
If omitted, output is written to standard output.
.It Fl -alpha Ar alphabet_file
Load a custom Base76 alphabet from
.Ar alphabet_file .
The file may contain arbitrary content, but only the first 76 unique 7-bit
characters (ASCII < 128) are used.
Whitespace characters are ignored, and duplicate characters are skipped.
If fewer than 76 unique 7-bit characters are found, the program exits with an
error.
.It Fl h , Fl -help
Display a help message and exit.
.It Fl -version
Display version information and exit.
.El
.Sh ALPHABET
By default, the Base76 alphabet is:
.Pp
.Bd -literal -offset indent
0123456789ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZabcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz!@#$%^&*()_+[]
.Ed
.Pp
When
.Fl -alpha
is used, the alphabet is constructed as follows:
.Bl -bullet -offset indent
.It
Only characters with ASCII value less than 128 are considered.
.It
Whitespace characters are ignored.
.It
Duplicate characters are ignored.
.It
The first 76 unique 7-bit characters encountered form the alphabet.
.It
If fewer than 76 unique characters are found, the program terminates with an
error.
.El
.Sh INPUT SIZE
The
.Nm
utility operates as a streaming pipeline and does not load the entire input
into memory.
Forward mode processes input byte-by-byte, and reverse mode processes Base76
tokens one at a time.
This allows processing of arbitrarily large inputs, limited only by available
I/O bandwidth and system limits.
.Sh EXIT STATUS
The
.Nm
utility exits 0 on success and >0 if an error occurs.
.Pp
The following exit codes are defined:
.Bl -tag -width Ds
.It 1
General usage error.
This includes missing arguments, invalid flag combinations, or failure to open
input or output files.
.It 2
Alphabet file error.
Returned when the file specified with
.Fl -alpha
cannot be opened, contains fewer than 76 unique 7-bit characters, or otherwise
fails validation.
.It 3
Invalid Base76 token encountered during reverse mode.
This includes characters not present in the active alphabet or tokens that
decode to values outside the byte range (0–255).
.It 4
Token length error.
Returned when a Base76 token in reverse mode exceeds the internal token buffer
size.
.It 5
Internal pipeline error.
Returned when an unexpected condition occurs during streaming conversion.
.It 6
Temporary stream creation failure.
Returned when the program cannot create an internal temporary stream for
message input.
.It 7
Output write failure.
Returned when writing to the output stream fails, for example due to disk full
or I/O errors.
.El
